{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01QMEZitLTMw5uzQgqcAhTmi","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The requests are all going to `[upstream-default-backend]` which means the host header `canary.example.com` is not matching any ingress rule in the nginx configuration. But I created an ingress with `host: canary.example.com`. \n\nThe critical errors I see:\n1. `cannot merge alternative backend demo-stable-echo-80 into hostname canary-alt.example.com that does not exist` \n2. `unable to find real backend for alternative backend demo-canary-echo-80. Deleting.`\n\nThe second error is very concerning: the nginx controller is **deleting** the canary-echo alternative backend because it can't find the real backend. But wait, these errors mention:\n- `demo-stable-echo-80` trying to merge into `canary-alt.example.com` - this is the `canary-alt` decoy ingress (with host `canary-alt.example.com`) pointing to `stable-echo`, but there's no primary ingress for `canary-alt.example.com`\n- `demo-canary-echo-80` - this is my `canary-canary` ingress pointing to `canary-echo`\n\nThe problem is that the nginx ingress controller is interpreting my `canary-canary` ingress (pointing to `canary-echo`) as needing to merge into the primary backend for `canary.example.com`... but it keeps reporting \"unable to find real backend for alternative backend demo-canary-echo-80. Deleting.\" This is confusing because the primary ingress `canary-stable` exists and has endpoints, so why is it deleting the canary backend? Looking at the controller logs, I'm seeing a warning that the `demo/canary-echo` service doesn't have any active endpoints, which might be why the controller is removing the canary backend.\n\nLet me trace through the timeline more carefully. The canary-stable ingress was created and synced at 10:30:46, but at that exact moment the canary-echo service had no endpoints yet (the pod was still starting up), so the controller deleted the alternative backend. The same thing happened with canary-canary at 10:30:47. Then the backend reloaded at 10:30:48, but even by 10:30:50 the canary-echo endpoints still weren't available.\n\nBy 10:30:56 the status was updated for both ingresses, and at 10:30:57 the controller synced again and continued deleting the canary-echo backend. When test requests came in at 10:30:59, both returned 404s—not just the canary request, but even the one without the X-Canary header. That's the real problem: the stable backend for canary.example.com isn't being served at all.\n\nThe configuration was reloaded at 10:30:48 without the canary-echo backend, which explains why the stable route isn't working. I need to check if the controller re-synced after the endpoints actually became ready, or if it's stuck in a state where it keeps deleting the backend before it has a chance to be used.\n\nLet me trigger a re-sync by touching the ingress to force an update.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2242,"cache_read_input_tokens":39191,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2242},"output_tokens":25,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8f58a7ff-9fc4-4050-8745-749d31d10add","uuid":"9fba7158-c175-4dd9-9315-3eb1cb19bb0e","request_id":"req_011Cc6nVuyuSzBXYMkAnLCnQ"}
